nd I stood up there and my father happened to come at - well, he didn't come up, sent me sister up. Said I was up there watching. I stood up - just on the corner - well you could only get so near 'cos the police - stood there and all of a sudden I - our M
e
l, come on down home, her says, your dad's in a - terrible temper, you're having it when you get in. Oh I'm coming in a minute, I didn't go. I stopped there and I did without me dinner. Always remember it. And - when I went down, teatime when I went down 
-
 hm, where have you been? I've been - standing up watching the men, I says, tip that dirt out. I'll tip you down, he says, I'll throw you down. So he says, have you had your dinner? I said, no. Well - aren't you hungry? I says, well I am, I says, but - I 
t
hought to myself I was hungry but I daren't say so. Any road, he says, well - I think best thing you can do is - get you ready for bed. I thought myself, yes, and get ready for bed, I shall come down again. Any road, I - I was just getting ready and - he 
p
ulled his belt off. Cut me right across me backside. He says, that's - that'll be one - that'll be one round and - I don't know, something else he said and - any road - just as he caught me across me backside I - opened the middle door and I shop upstairs
.
 He says, all right, he says, you've got to come down again. I thought to myself, yes, I didn't come down, I - I stopped - I got in bed and stopped there. But - the time, it'd be about nine o'clock I think it was, half past nine - me sister come up and sa
